Type-II Error Simulation

Visualizations of the results can be found here: Tableau Dashboard

The purpose of this report is to outline in detail the analysis procedure used to generate the results when the alternate hypothesis is true. The outcome measures include:

  1. Type-II error rate
  2. Power
  3. Experimental and control means
  4. Experimental and control standard deviations

The large amount of data makes it challenging to understand because there would be too many visualizations to look through. For this reason the table will be exported and a Tableau dashboard will be created to enable quick filtering and comparisons.

Mixed anova power function

# function ---------------------------------------------------------------
anova.pwr.mixed <- function(data, Formula, n, m, rho, n.needed=FALSE) {
  require(stringr)
  Formula <- formula(paste(Formula, "+Error(group)"))               # aov formula
  x <- summary(aov(Formula, data))          # aov model
  terms <- c(rownames(x[[1]][[1]]), rownames(x[[2]][[1]])) # terms in model
  terms <- str_pad(terms, max(nchar(terms)), "right")      # fix typography
  
  pwr <- function(n) {
    k <- length(unique(study$group))          # n groups
    sigma <- mean(data$SD)                    # sigma
    data$n <- n                               # n per group
    N <- sum(with(data, tapply(n,group,unique))) # total N
    x <- summary(aov(Formula, data))          # aov model
    var_b <- x[[1]][[1]][[2]] / (k*m)         # SS between 
    var_w <- x[[2]][[1]][[2]] / (k*m)         # SS within
    f_between <- sqrt(var_b / sigma^2)        # f between
    f_within <- sqrt(var_w / sigma^2)         # f within
    
    # Degrees of freedom ------------------------------------------------------
    df1_b <- x[[1]][[1]][[1]]              # df model between
    df1_w <- x[[2]][[1]][[1]]              # df model within
    df1 <- c(df1_b, df1_w)
    df2_b <- N-1-sum(df1_b)                # df error between
    df2_w <- (N*m-1) - (N-1) - sum(df1_w)  # df error within
    
    # Power Between -----------------------------------------------------------------
    lambda <- N * (m/(1+(m-1)*rho)) * f_between^2        # lambda between
    F_critical <- qf(0.05,df1_b,df2_b, lower.tail=FALSE) # F critical between
    power_b <- pf(F_critical, df1_b, df2_b, lambda, lower.tail=FALSE) # power between
    
    # Power Within -----------------------------------------------------------------
    lambda <- (N * m * f_within^2) / (1 - rho)           # lambda within
    F_critical <- qf(0.05,df1_w,df2_w, lower.tail=FALSE) # F critical within
    power_w <- pf(F_critical, df1_w, df2_w, lambda, lower.tail=FALSE) # power within
    c("b" = power_b, "w" = power_w)
  }
  
  # Get n for desired power -------------------------------------------------
  power <- pwr(n) # get powr for 'n'
  if(n.needed) {
    n_needed <- rep(NA, length(power)) # pre-create object
    # loop til desired power is found
    for(i in 1:length(power)) {
      n2 <- 5
      while(pwr(n2)[i] < 0.8) n2 <- n2+1
      n_needed[i] <- n2 
    }
  } else n_needed <- NA

  
  # output ------------------------------------------------------------------
  out <- data.frame(terms, "power" = round(power, 3),
                    "n.needed" = n_needed) # n per group
  names(out)[1] <- str_pad("Terms", max(nchar(terms)), "right")
  out
}

Simulation Procedure Type-II Error

Dataset production

  1. Using the sample size, randomly subset samples (ERP waveforms) from the population dataset. The subset of the data drawn from the population dataset without replacement is twice the sample size selected.

  2. To create the control condition, randomly subset a number of samples from the subsetted data set equal to the sample size.

  3. To create the experimental conditions data set, remove the control conditions data from the subsetted dataset to leave the remaining samples

  4. Add the calculated effect size difference to each data point

  5. Subsetting out the time window (300-500 ms) in which we believe the P3 amplitude will fall within

Applying the peak-picking methodologies

  1. Calculate the peak amplitudes of each sample and condition

  2. Calculate the adaptive mean amplitudes of each sample and condition by first finding the peak amplitude and calculating the mean over a 50 second time window spanning the peak amplitude

  3. Calculate the mean amplitudes of each sample and condition by finding the mean over the time window of interest

Combining all of the peak-picking methodologies data together into one large dataframe

  1. Label and combine all of the peak-picking methodologies data together

Means

  1. Calculating means of each peak-picking methodology by condition and generating a new dataset

Conducting an ANOVAs

  1. Perform an ANOVA with the P3 amplitude as a dependent variable and fixed effects with condition and peak-picking methodology

  2. Performing an ANOVA for each peak-picking methodology with the P3 amplitude as a dependent variable and a fixed effect of condition. Store the p-values in a new dataframe, and use these values later to calculate the type-I error rate.

Post-Hoc testing

  1. Perform a Tukey’s HSD post-hoc test on the anova model with the condition and peak-picking methodology fixed effects

  2. Generate a new dataset containing the p-values from the Tukey HSD post-hoc test

Calculate the type-II error rate

  1. Calculate the type-II error rate and power.
set.seed(1234)

peak_pvalue_dist = data.frame()

simulation_number = 1000
numTests <- simulation_number  #number of t-test
alphaSet = c(0.05)  #set of alpha values to test
sigTests <- data.frame()
pvalue_dist = data.frame()
allmeans = data.frame()
post_hoc_results_temp1 = data.frame()
post_hoc_results_temp2 = data.frame()
post_hoc_results_condition = data.frame()
post_hoc_results_method = data.frame() 
all.peak.result = data.frame()
all.mean.result = data.frame()
all.adaptive.mean.result = data.frame()


sample_size = unlist(seq(10, 100, 10))
# sample_size = 10
effect_size = seq(0.1, 1, by = .1)
# effect_size = 0.1

for (s in sample_size){

  
  for (e in effect_size){
  
    #Starting the simulation
    counter <- 1 #keeps track of row numbers in the output table
    for (i in 1:numTests) {

        #Sample the necessary number of sample from the popultion dataset (2 times: one for each condition)
        temp = ERP2_PZ[ERP2_PZ$sample %in% sample(unique(ERP2_PZ$sample), 
                                        size = s * 2,
                                        replace = FALSE), ]
        
        #Checking to see if we subsetted 80 unique samples
        # length(unique(temp$sample))
        
        #Then randomly sample the control condition from the temp data
        control_condition = temp[temp$sample %in% sample(unique(temp$sample), 
                                                size = s,
                                                replace = FALSE), ]
        
        #Checking to see if we subsetted half the number unique samples from temp
        # length(unique(control_condition$sample))
        
        control_condition$condition = "control"
        
        #Remove those samples from the original dataset, and the remaining trials become the experimental condition
        experimental_condition = temp[!temp$sample %in% control_condition$sample, ]
        
        #Checking to see if we remove the unique samples used for the control condition
        length(unique(experimental_condition$sample))
      
        experimental_condition$condition = "experimental"
        
        #Increasing the voltage of the experimental condition to make the null hypothesis false
        #Do this by adding a value calculated by using the effect size and pooled standard deviation of
        #the population dataset
        experimental_condition$PZ = experimental_condition$PZ + value(e, ERP2_PZ$PZ)
        
        #Combining the experimental and control conditions together
        conditions_combined = rbind(experimental_condition, control_condition)
  
        #Subsetting out the time window we expect the P3 to fall within
        data = conditions_combined[(conditions_combined$TIME >= 300 & 
                                               conditions_combined$TIME <= 500),]
        
        
        #======================================================================================#
        #Generating peak and mean amplitudes
        #======================================================================================#
        #Calculating the peak amplitude
        peak_amps_erp = setDT(data)[, .SD[which.max(PZ)], by = list(sample, condition)]
        
        peak_amps_erp = peak_amps_erp[, c("sample", "condition", "PZ")]

        peak_amps_erp$method = "Peak Amplitude"
        
        
        #======================================================================================#
        #Calculating the adaptive mean amplitude

        #This way seems to work if you want to use more than one index
        mean_amps_erp1 = rbind(setDT(data)[, .SD[c(which.max(PZ) - 1)], by = list(sample, condition)],
                               setDT(data)[, .SD[c(which.max(PZ) - 2)], by = list(sample, condition)],
                               setDT(data)[, .SD[c(which.max(PZ) - 3)], by = list(sample, condition)],
                               setDT(data)[, .SD[c(which.max(PZ) - 4)], by = list(sample, condition)])
        
        
        mean_amps_erp = setDT(data)[, .SD[c(
                                       which.max(PZ),
                                       which.max(PZ) + 1,
                                       which.max(PZ) + 2,
                                       which.max(PZ) + 3,
                                       which.max(PZ) + 4
                                       # which.max(PZ) + 5
                                       )], 
                                    by = list(sample, condition)]
        
        mean_amps_erp = na.omit(rbind(mean_amps_erp, mean_amps_erp1))
        
        mean_amps_erp = mean_amps_erp[, c("sample", "condition", "PZ")]
        
        mean_amps_erp = setDT(mean_amps_erp)[ , mean(PZ), by = list(sample, condition)]

        colnames(mean_amps_erp) = c("sample", "condition", "PZ")

        mean_amps_erp$method = "Adaptive Mean Amplitude"
        
        #======================================================================================#
        #Calculating the mean amplitude
        mean2_amps_erp = aggregate(. ~ sample + condition, data, FUN = mean)
        
        mean2_amps_erp = na.omit(mean2_amps_erp)
        
        mean2_amps_erp = mean2_amps_erp[, c("sample", "condition", "PZ")]
        
        mean2_amps_erp$method = "Mean Amplitude"
        
        
        #======================================================================================#
        #Combined all 3 datasets together
        #======================================================================================#
        
        peak_methods = rbind(peak_amps_erp, mean_amps_erp, mean2_amps_erp)
        
        #======================================================================================#
        #Calculating the p-values for the anova
        #======================================================================================#
        test.result = lm(PZ ~ condition*method, peak_methods)
        
        #Putting together all of the data into a dataframe
        sigTests[counter, 1] = anova(test.result)$'Pr(>F)'[1]
        sigTests[counter, 2] = anova(test.result)$'Pr(>F)'[2]
        sigTests[counter, 3] = s #sample size
        sigTests[counter, 4] = e #effect size
        sigTests[counter, 5] = i #simulation number

        #Calculating all of the means used in the linear model
        means = aggregate(PZ ~ condition + method, peak_methods, FUN = mean)
        means[, 4] = s #sample size
        means[, 5] = e #effect size
        means[, 6] = i #simulation number
        
        allmeans = rbind(allmeans, means)
        
        #======================================================================================#
        #Calculating the p-values for the post-hoc test
        #======================================================================================#
        post_hoc_results = TukeyHSD(aov(PZ ~ condition*method, peak_methods)) #Confidence level is 95%
        
        post_hoc_results_temp1 = as.data.frame(post_hoc_results[1])
        post_hoc_results_temp1[, 5] = s #sample size
        post_hoc_results_temp1[, 6] = e #effect size
        post_hoc_results_temp1[, 7] = i #simulation number
        
        post_hoc_results_temp2 = as.data.frame(post_hoc_results[2])
        post_hoc_results_temp2[, 5] = s #sample size
        post_hoc_results_temp2[, 6] = e #effect size
        post_hoc_results_temp2[, 7] = i #simulation number
        
        post_hoc_results_condition = rbind(post_hoc_results_condition, post_hoc_results_temp1)
        post_hoc_results_method = rbind(post_hoc_results_method, post_hoc_results_temp2)

        
        #======================================================================================#
        #Calculating the p-values for each methodology to see if there's a condition effect
        #======================================================================================#
        peak.result = anova(lm(PZ ~ condition, peak_methods[peak_methods$method == "Peak Amplitude", ]))
        peak.result = peak.result[1, ]
        peak.result[, 6] = s #sample size
        peak.result[, 7] = e #effect size
        peak.result[, 8] = i #simulation number
        

        adaptive.mean.result = anova(lm(PZ ~ condition, peak_methods[peak_methods$method == "Adaptive Mean Amplitude", ]))
        adaptive.mean.result = adaptive.mean.result[1, ]
        adaptive.mean.result[, 6] = s #sample size
        adaptive.mean.result[, 7] = e #effect size
        adaptive.mean.result[, 8] = i #simulation number

        mean.result = anova(lm(PZ ~ condition, peak_methods[peak_methods$method == "Mean Amplitude", ]))
        mean.result = mean.result[1, ]
        mean.result[, 6] = s #sample size
        mean.result[, 7] = e #effect size
        mean.result[, 8] = i #simulation number
        
        
        #Rbinding to larger dataframe
        all.peak.result = rbind(all.peak.result, peak.result)
        all.adaptive.mean.result = rbind(all.adaptive.mean.result, adaptive.mean.result)
        all.mean.result = rbind(all.mean.result, mean.result)

        counter <- counter + 1 #move to the next row
    }
    
    
    pvalue_dist = rbind(pvalue_dist, sigTests)

  }
}

#Setting column names
colnames(pvalue_dist)[1:5] = c("condition", "method", "sample_size", "effect_size", "sample")

#Finding the type II error and power
all.results$typeIIerror = ifelse(all.results$`Pr(>F)` > 0.05, 1, 0)
all.results2 = aggregate(. ~ sample_size + effect_size + method, all.results, FUN = sum)
all.results2$typeIIerror = (all.results2$typeIIerror/numTests)*100
all.results2$power = 100 - all.results2$typeIIerror


#Calculating the type II error and power
sigTests_typetwo = aggregate(. ~ sample_size + effect_size, pvalue_dist, FUN =sum)
sigTests_typetwo$condition_power = numTests - sigTests_typetwo$condition_typeIIerror
sigTests_typetwo$method_power = numTests - sigTests_typetwo$method__typeIIerror

Analyzing the Means

MEAN - ANOVA

We would be an interaction between condition and effect size and no interaction between condition and methodology

Outcomes:

  • Main effect of condition

  • Main effect of effect size

  • Main effect of methodology

  • Main effect of sample size (May be by chance)

  • Condition by effect size interaction

CONCLUSIONS

  • P3 amplitude means are larger in the experimental condition compared to the control

  • P3 amplitude means differ among peak-picking methodologies

  • Peak methodology produces the largest P3 amplitudes, followed by the adaptive mean and mean methodologies

  • P3 amplitudes in the experimental condition increase as effect size increases

  • P3 amplitude means are similar across sample sizes

  • Power increases as effect sizes increases

  • Power increases as sample size increases

  • Peak-picking methodologies power seems to differ at lower effect sizes and converges as the effect size becomes larger

  • The mean methodology’s power differs from the peak and adaptive mean’s across sample sizes

  • The mean methodology’s power appears to be consistently higher

  • A peak-picking methodologies power will increase faster when sample size and effect size rise
